<!--headed paper--><!--
<p rend="right">ROLF ITALIAANDER <lb/></p>
<p rend="right"><placeName>Hamburg 20 Beilwigstr 39</placeName> <lb/></p>
<p rend="right"><placeName>West Germany</placeName> <lb/></p>
--><!--<p><supplied reason="damage">D.</supplied>Livingston an H. Barth <lb/></p>-->
<lb/><p rend="right"><placeName>57 Sloane Str.</placeName></p>
<lb/><p>20<hi rend="sup">th</hi> May 1857 </p>
<lb/><p>My Dear Sir </p>
<lb/><p>I beg leave to tender you my <add place="above">hearty</add> thanks for your kindness in 
<w>sen-<lb break="no"/>ding</w> me a copy of your handsome work. </p>
<lb/><p>I was not aware <choice><sic>untill</sic><corr>until</corr></choice> I read your note that any questions had 
<lb/>been raised such as those to which you refer and feel no <del type="strikethrough">certain</del> <add place="above">sort of</add>
<lb/>interest in their solution. And as for the difficulties they seem 
<lb/>to have been some what different in their nature. I judge this from 
<lb/>a glance at part of your preface. But we have overcome them and 
<lb/>nothing more need be said about them. </p>
<lb/><p>I anticipate much pleasure in reading your volumes and thank 
<lb/>you sincerely for <choice><sic>tehm</sic><corr>them</corr></choice> and the sentences of approbation with which 
<lb/>you kindly accompanied the gift. </p>
<lb/><p>I am Sir </p>
<lb/><p rend="center">your much </p>
<lb/><p rend="center">obeyed St. </p>
<lb/><p rend="center">David Livingston </p>
<lb/><p><persName>Dr Barth</persName></p>
			
